(1) review the steps which the parties have taken in the preparation of the case, and in particular their compliance with any directions that the court may have given,

(2) decide and give directions about the steps which are to be taken to secure the progress of the claim in accordance with the overriding objective, and

(3) ensure as far as it can that all agreements that can be reached between the parties about the matters in issue and the conduct of the claim are made and recorded.", "filepath": "Practice Direction 29", "groups": [], "id": "Practice_Direction_29_subsection_32", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "Practice_Direction_29", "reranker_score": 2.4273126125335693, "score": 0.014705882407724857, "sourcefile": "Practice Direction 29", "sourcepage": "Practice Direction 29", "storageUrl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29", "subsection_id": "5.1", "subsection_index": 32, "total_subsections": 64, "updated": "2017-01-30T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "5.2, Practice Direction 29, Practice Direction 29", "content": "5.2

(1) Rule 29.3(2) provides that where a party has a legal representative, a representative familiar with the case and with sufficient authority to deal with any issues that are likely to arise must attend case management conferences and pre-trial reviews.

(2) That person should be someone who is personally involved in the conduct of the case, and who has the authority and information to deal with any matter which may reasonably be expected to be dealt with at such a hearing, including the fixing of the timetable, the identification of issues and matters of evidence.

(3) Where the inadequacy of the person attending or of his instructions leads to the adjournment of a hearing, the court will expect to make a wasted costs order.", "filepath": "Practice Direction 29", "groups": [], "id": "Practice_Direction_29_subsection_33", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "Practice_Direction_29", "reranker_score": 2.4273126125335693, "score": 0.014705882407724857, "sourcefile": "Practice Direction 29", "sourcepage": "Practice Direction 29", "storageUrl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29", "subsection_id": "5.2", "subsection_index": 33, "total_subsections": 64, "updated": "2017-01-30T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "5.3, Practice Direction 29, Practice Direction 29", "content": "5.3 The topics the court will consider at a case management conference are likely to include:

(1) whether the claimant has made clear the claim he is bringing, in particular the amount he is claiming, so that the other party can understand the case he has to meet,

(2) whether any amendments are required to the claim, a statement of case or any other document,

(3) what disclosure of documents, if any, is necessary,

(4) what expert evidence is reasonably required in accordance with rule 35.1 and how and when that evidence should be obtained and disclosed,

(5) what factual evidence should be disclosed,

(6) what arrangements should be made about the giving of clarification or further information and the putting of questions to experts, and

(7) whether it will be just and will save costs to order a split trial or the trial of one or more preliminary issues.", "filepath": "Practice Direction 29", "groups": [], "id": "Practice_Direction_29_subsection_34", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "Practice_Direction_29", "reranker_score": 2.4273126125335693, "score": 0.014705882407724857, "sourcefile": "Practice Direction 29", "sourcepage": "Practice Direction 29", "storageUrl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29", "subsection_id": "5.3", "subsection_index": 34, "total_subsections": 64, "updated": "2017-01-30T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "5.4, Practice Direction 29, Practice Direction 29", "content": "5.4 In all cases the court will set a timetable for the steps it decides are necessary to be taken. These steps may include the holding of a case management conference or a pre-trial review, and the court will be alert to perform its duty to fix a trial date or period as soon as it can.", "filepath": "Practice Direction 29", "groups": [], "id": "Practice_Direction_29_subsection_35", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "Practice_Direction_29", "reranker_score": 2.4273126125335693, "score": 0.014705882407724857, "sourcefile": "Practice Direction 29", "sourcepage": "Practice Direction 29", "storageUrl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29", "subsection_id": "5.4", "subsection_index": 35, "total_subsections": 64, "updated": "2017-01-30T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "5.5, Practice Direction 29, Practice Direction 29", "content": "5.5

(1) The court will not at this stage give permission to use expert evidence unless it can identify each expert by name or field in its order and say whether his evidence is to be given orally or by the use of his report.

(2) A party who obtains expert evidence before obtaining a direction about it does so at his own risk as to costs, except where he obtained the evidence in compliance with a pre-action protocol.", "filepath": "Practice Direction 29", "groups": [], "id": "Practice_Direction_29_subsection_36", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "Practice_Direction_29", "reranker_score": 2.4273126125335693, "score": 0.014705882407724857, "sourcefile": "Practice Direction 29", "sourcepage": "Practice Direction 29", "storageUrl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29", "subsection_id": "5.5", "subsection_index": 36, "total_subsections": 64, "updated": "2017-01-30T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "5.6, Practice Direction 29, Practice Direction 29", "content": "5.6 To assist the court, the parties and their legal advisers should:

(1) ensure that all documents that the court is likely to ask to see (including witness statements and experts' reports) are brought to the hearing,

(2) consider whether the parties should attend,

(3) consider whether a case summary will be useful, and

(4) consider what orders each wishes to be made and give notice of them to the other parties.", "filepath": "Practice Direction 29", "groups": [], "id": "Practice_Direction_29_subsection_37", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "Practice_Direction_29", "reranker_score": 2.4273126125335693, "score": 0.014705882407724857, "sourcefile": "Practice Direction 29", "sourcepage": "Practice Direction 29", "storageUrl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29", "subsection_id": "5.6", "subsection_index": 37, "total_subsections": 64, "updated": "2017-01-30T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "5.7, Practice Direction 29, Practice Direction 29", "content": "5.7

(1) A case summary:

(a) should be designed to assist the court to understand and deal with the questions before it,

(b) should set out a brief chronology of the claim, the issues of fact which are agreed or in dispute and the evidence needed to decide them,

(c) should not normally exceed 500 words in length, and

(d) should be prepared by the claimant and agreed with the other parties if possible.", "filepath": "Practice Direction 29", "groups": [], "id": "Practice_Direction_29_subsection_38", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "Practice_Direction_29", "reranker_score": 2.4273126125335693, "score": 0.014705882407724857, "sourcefile": "Practice Direction 29", "sourcepage": "Practice Direction 29", "storageUrl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29", "subsection_id": "5.7", "subsection_index": 38, "total_subsections": 64, "updated": "2017-01-30T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "5.8, Practice Direction 29, Practice Direction 29", "content": "5.8

(1) Where a party wishes to obtain an order not routinely made at a case management conference and believes that his application will be opposed, he should issue and serve the application in time for it to be heard at the case management conference.

(2) If the time allowed for the case management conference is likely to be insufficient for the application to be heard he should inform the court at once so that a fresh date can be fixed.

(3) A costs sanction may be imposed on a party who fails to comply with sub-paragraph (1) or (2).", "filepath": "Practice Direction 29", "groups": [], "id": "Practice_Direction_29_subsection_39", "is_subsection": true, "oids": [], "original_doc_id": "Practice_Direction_29", "reranker_score": 2.4273126125335693, "score": 0.014705882407724857, "sourcefile": "Practice Direction 29", "sourcepage": "Practice Direction 29", "storageUrl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29", "storageurl": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29", "subsection_id": "5.8", "subsection_index": 39, "total_subsections": 64, "updated": "2017-01-30T00:00:00Z", "url": "https://www.justice.gov.uk/courts/procedure-rules/civil/rules/part29/pd_part29"}, {"category": "Civil Procedure Rules and Practice Directions", "citation": "5.9, Practice Direction 29, Practice Direction 29", "content": "5.9 At a case management conference the court may also consider whether the case ought to be tried by a High Court judge or by a judge who specialises in that type of claim and how that question will be decided. In that case the claim may need to be transferred to another court.

